Class DistinctQueue<E>

      xxl.core.collections.queues.DistinctQueue<E>
Type Parameters:
E - the type of the elements of this queue.
All Implemented Interfaces:
Queue<E>
public class DistinctQueue<E>
extends DecoratorQueue<E>

This class provides a wrapper for a queue that performes a simple duplicate elimination. When inserting a row duplicate elements, this class' enqueue method only inserts the first element and ignors the rest. Every time the insertion of duplicate elements is separated by another element's insertion, the duplicate elements are not detected by the enqueue method. This duplicate elimination is very important for some operations like sorting etc. For example it can be used to integrate an early duplicate elimination into a physical sort operation instead of proceeding it on the sorted data. One example is the SortMerge cursor of this library. The destinct queue can be used to eliminate duplicates while merging the runs.

Usage example (1). 

     // create a new queue
 
     Queue<Integer> q1 = new ListQueue<Integer>();

     // open the queue

     q1.open();

     // create an iteration over 10000 random Integers (between 0 and
     // 100)
 
     Cursor<Integer> cursor = new DiscreteRandomNumber(new JavaDiscreteRandomWrapper(100), 10000);
 
     // insert all elements of the given cursor
 
     for (; cursor.hasNext(); q1.enqueue(cursor.next()));
     
     // print the size of the queue after insertion
                
     System.out.println("Size q1:\t" + q1.size());

     // reset the cursor, so that it can be used again
     
     cursor.reset();

     // create a new distinct queue
                
     Queue<Integer> q2 = new DistinctQueue<Integer>(new ListQueue<Integer>());

     // opent the queue

     q2.open();
     
     // insert all elements of the given cursor

     for (; cursor.hasNext(); q2.enqueue(cursor.next()));

     // print the size of the distinct queue after insertion

     System.out.println("Size q2:\t" + q2.size());

     // close the open queues and the cursor after use

     q1.close();
     q2.close();
     cursor.close();

Field Detail

FACTORY_METHOD

public static final Function<Object,DistinctQueue<Object>> FACTORY_METHOD
A factory method to create a new DistinctQueue (see contract for FACTORY_METHOD in interface Queue). It may be invoked with a parameter list (for further details see Function) of queues, an iterator or without any parameters. A parameter list of queues will be used to initialize the wrapped queue with the queue at index 0 and an iterator will be used to insert the contained elements into the new DistinctQueue.

See Also:
Function

last

protected E last
The field last is used to store the object that is inserted into the queue at last. When another element should be inserted into the queue, it is compared with last. When the elements are not equal, it is inserted into the queue and last is set to it.

Method Detail

enqueue

public void enqueue(E object)
             throws IllegalStateException
Appends the specified element to the end of this queue. The end of the queue is given by its strategy.
This method performs a simple duplicate elimination. When inserting a row duplicate elements, it only inserts the first element and ignors the rest. Every time the insertion of duplicate elements is separated by another element's insertion, the duplicate elements are not detected by this method.
